{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528740"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:46:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:46:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14327"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14327"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.65,0.03,0.17,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7022"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111786"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7022"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14327"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93856"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3031"},{"type":"tags","id":"3151"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11691"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16689"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45750"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111786"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about her long-standing low mood. She reports feeling \u0027down\u0027 most of the time for the past three years. She describes having low energy, poor appetite, and difficulty concentrating at work. Despite these symptoms, she has been able to maintain her job and relationships, although she finds them challenging. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She denies any thoughts of self-harm or suicide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well-groomed but speaks in a slow, quiet manner. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Mental state examination reveals a depressed mood and affect, with no evidence of psychotic symptoms or cognitive impairment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cyclothymic disorder","Persistent depressive disorder","Adjustment disorder with depressed mood","Major depressive disorder","Bipolar II disorder"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the clinical presentation, the most likely diagnosis for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Epersistent depressive disorder\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as dysthymia. This condition is characterised by a chronic depressed mood that lasts for at least two years in adults (one year in children and adolescents). The patient\u0027s symptoms have been present for three years, meeting this duration criterion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMajor depressive disorder\u003C/strong\u003E typically involves more severe symptoms that significantly impair daily functioning. While this patient\u0027s symptoms are affecting her life, she has been able to maintain her job and relationships, which is more consistent with persistent depressive disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBipolar II disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves alternating episodes of hypomania and depression. There is no evidence in this case of hypomanic episodes, making this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECyclothymic disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by numerous periods of hypomanic symptoms and periods of depressive symptoms that do not meet criteria for a major depressive episode. The chronic nature of this patient\u0027s symptoms and lack of hypomanic periods make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdjustment disorder with depressed mood\u003C/strong\u003E is typically triggered by a specific stressor and lasts for a shorter duration (usually resolving within six months of the stressor\u0027s termination). The chronic nature of this patient\u0027s symptoms and lack of a specific triggering event make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that persistent depressive disorder can coexist with episodes of major depression, a condition known as \u0027double depression\u0027. Treatment typically involves a combination of psychotherapy (such as cognitive-behavioural therapy) and antidepressant medication. The chronic nature of persistent depressive disorder often requires long-term management and follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Persistent depressive disorder (dysthymia) is characterised by a chronic depressed mood lasting at least two years in adults.","Persistent depressive disorder can coexist with major depressive episodes, a condition known as \u0027double depression\u0027.","Treatment for persistent depressive disorder typically involves a combination of psychotherapy and antidepressant medication."],"references":["American Psychiatric Association DS, American Psychiatric Association DS. Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders: DSM-5. Washington, DC: American psychiatric association; 2013 May 22."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93856"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14327"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93856"},"attr